Note:
This file implements the DESCRIPTOR-HEAP variant of the Runa runtime memory
system: a per-heap-descriptor bump allocator backed by an mmap region, with a
metadata struct (OwnedHeap) describing one independent heap instance.

OWNED HEAP (Per-Descriptor) - Bump Allocator With Owner-Scoped Lifetime
- Process bump allocations against a self-contained mmap-backed buffer
- Handle per-descriptor heap creation, destruction, reset, clear, and clone
- Manage resize, grow, shrink, compact (no-op for bump allocators), and merge
- Provide query operations for size, capacity, usage, peak, allocation count
- Provide performance instrumentation (stats, profile, optimize, benchmark)
- Provide debugging surface (validate, dump, trace, leak check, verify)

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- The per-descriptor heap fills the gap between the single-buffer Arena
  (runtime/core/memory/arena.runa) and the global owned-heap free-list allocator
  in compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa: it provides multiple
  independent bump arenas each with its own mmap region, lifetime, owner field,
  and statistics surface. Useful for plugin sandboxing, per-pass compilation
  heaps, per-thread scratch areas, and any future workload that wants O(1)
  bulk-free with named ownership.
- The 34 Processes form a coherent per-descriptor API surface independent of
  the registry-tracked global owned-heap subsystem. Callers that want a heap
  they can destroy at a known point in time without scanning a global registry
  use this engine.
- Bump-allocator semantics under the "owned heap" label is documented honestly
  here in the @Reasoning blocks: the user-visible allocate function returns a
  pointer that is invalidated only when the descriptor itself is reset, cleared,
  destroyed, or resized. There is no per-allocation free. This is the same
  shape as the Arena in arena.runa, but with a richer per-instance metadata
  surface and an explicit owner field that lets a parent subsystem reclaim its
  child heaps deterministically.

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- Descriptor lifecycle: create, destroy, reset, clear, clone
- Allocation: allocate, allocate_aligned, allocate_zeroed, allocate_array,
  allocate_string, allocate_struct
- Memory management: resize, grow, shrink, compact (no-op), merge
- Query: get_size, get_capacity, get_usage, get_peak_usage, get_fragmentation,
  get_allocation_count, is_full, has_space, descriptor_get_size
- Performance: get_stats, reset_stats, profile, optimize, benchmark
- Debugging: validate, dump, trace, check_leaks, verify

Migration history:
- 2026-05-18: Moved from compiler/internal/owned_utils.runa into the runtime
  tree per the CEO-ratified "memory management lives in runtime/core/memory/"
  ruling. Three unused imports (MemorySafety, DebugUtils, Collections) were
  stripped during the move. A broken import path
  (compiler/frontend/primitives/core/syscall_core.runa, which does not exist
  on disk) was repointed at the canonical compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/
  syscall.runa as used by arena.runa. The mmap/munmap calls were rewritten from
  raw syscall_6/syscall_2 with hardcoded Linux syscall numbers to use the
  cross-platform syscall_mmap/syscall_munmap abstractions exposed by the
  syscall module. The mremap call retains its raw form because no abstracted
  wrapper exists; it remains Linux-specific and is documented as such on the
  resize Process. The owned_heap_get_size Process was renamed to
  owned_heap_descriptor_get_size to avoid name collision with the new
  registry-aware owned_heap_get_size in runtime/core/memory/owned_heap_wrappers.runa
  (different signature, different semantics, both retained). Zero external
  callers existed for any of the 34 Processes so the rename is safe.

  Pre-migration the file also served as an import-alias re-exporter for
  allocate/deallocate via transitive resolution through MemoryUtils to Layout.
  That role has been retired: all 26 caller files now import MemoryLayout
  directly, eliminating the alias indirection.

Dependencies:
- Imports compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa for the canonical
  TIER-3 owned-heap allocate/deallocate used to allocate descriptor structs
  and ancillary diagnostic blobs.
- Imports compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa for raw memory
  qword reads, writes, copies, zeroing, and byte writes.
- Imports compiler/frontend/primitives/core/bitwise_core.runa for power-of-two
  alignment arithmetic.
- Imports compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa for mmap, munmap,
  the raw mremap dispatch, and clock_gettime in benchmark.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as MemoryLayout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/bitwise_core.runa" as BitwiseCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa" as Syscall

Note:
============================================================================
OwnedHeap Structure Definitions
============================================================================
:End Note

Note:
OwnedHeap structure layout (80 bytes, 10 qwords):
  Offset  0: memory_block        Pointer to mmap-backed data buffer
  Offset  8: current_pos         Bump pointer position within the data buffer
  Offset 16: size                Logical size of the data buffer in bytes
  Offset 24: capacity            Physical (mmap-reserved) capacity in bytes
  Offset 32: alignment           Default alignment for allocate (power of 2)
  Offset 40: owner               Opaque owner-pointer field (caller-defined)
  Offset 48: is_owned            1 if descriptor owns its memory_block, else 0
  Offset 56: allocation_count    Lifetime count of allocate calls that succeeded
  Offset 64: peak_usage          Max current_pos observed across descriptor lifetime
  Offset 72: reserved            Padding qword to keep 16-byte struct alignment

Allocations against this descriptor are pointer-bump increments: current_pos
moves forward by the (alignment-padded) size, and the returned pointer is
memory_block + aligned_pos. There is NO per-allocation header. Individual
free is not supported - the descriptor as a whole is the unit of free.

Note that size and capacity coincide today (size is set to capacity at create
and after resize). The two fields are retained as distinct slots to allow
future logical-vs-physical distinction (e.g., a descriptor that has reserved
more pages than it has committed) without breaking the on-disk layout.
:End Note

Type called "OwnedHeap":
    memory_block as Integer    Note: Pointer to allocated memory block
    current_pos as Integer     Note: Current bump pointer position
    size as Integer            Note: Logical size of buffer
    capacity as Integer        Note: Physical mmap-reserved capacity
    alignment as Integer       Note: Default alignment (power of 2)
    owner as Integer           Note: Opaque owner reference
    is_owned as Integer        Note: 1 if descriptor owns memory_block, else 0
    allocation_count as Integer Note: Lifetime successful-allocate count
    peak_usage as Integer      Note: Max current_pos observed
End Type

Note:
OwnedAllocation structure layout (56 bytes, 7 qwords):
  Offset  0: heap            Pointer to parent OwnedHeap descriptor
  Offset  8: memory_ptr      Pointer to the allocation
  Offset 16: size            Size of the allocation in bytes
  Offset 24: alignment       Alignment used for this allocation
  Offset 32: owner           Opaque owner reference for this allocation
  Offset 40: is_freed        1 if individually freed (reserved for future)
  Offset 48: next            Pointer to next OwnedAllocation in a chain

This Type is declared for forward compatibility with a per-allocation tracking
list that the migration plan flagged as an unrealised design intent. Today no
allocate path instantiates this struct; the structure shape is reserved so
that a future per-allocation registry can be bolted on without breaking the
existing descriptor layout.
:End Note

Type called "OwnedAllocation":
    heap as Integer            Note: Parent OwnedHeap descriptor
    memory_ptr as Integer      Note: Allocation address
    size as Integer            Note: Allocation size in bytes
    alignment as Integer       Note: Allocation alignment
    owner as Integer           Note: Opaque per-allocation owner
    is_freed as Integer        Note: Reserved for per-allocation free
    next as Integer            Note: Forward link for allocation chain
End Type

Note:
OwnedHeapStats structure layout (48 bytes, 6 qwords):
  Offset  0: total_allocations  Lifetime allocate-call count
  Offset  8: total_bytes        Current allocated-bytes count (current_pos)
  Offset 16: peak_usage         Peak bytes-in-use observed
  Offset 24: fragmentation      Always 0 for a bump allocator
  Offset 32: allocation_time    Reserved future field (currently 0)
  Offset 40: deallocation_time  Reserved future field (currently 0)

Returned by owned_heap_get_stats. The returned pointer is itself an owned-heap
allocation that the caller must release via MemoryLayout.deallocate when done.
:End Note

Type called "OwnedHeapStats":
    total_allocations as Integer Note: Lifetime allocate count
    total_bytes as Integer       Note: Current allocated bytes
    peak_usage as Integer        Note: Peak bytes-in-use
    fragmentation as Integer     Note: 0 for bump allocators
    allocation_time as Integer   Note: Reserved (0)
    deallocation_time as Integer Note: Reserved (0)
End Type

Note:
============================================================================
OwnedHeap Constants
============================================================================
:End Note

Constant OWNED_HEAP_DEFAULT_SIZE as Integer is 131072       Note: 128KB default
Constant OWNED_HEAP_MIN_SIZE as Integer is 8192             Note: 8KB minimum
Constant OWNED_HEAP_MAX_SIZE as Integer is 2147483648       Note: 2GB maximum
Constant OWNED_HEAP_ALIGNMENT as Integer is 16              Note: default 16-byte align
Constant OWNED_HEAP_GROWTH_FACTOR as Integer is 2           Note: doubling growth
Constant OWNED_HEAP_SHRINK_THRESHOLD as Integer is 4        Note: shrink at 1/4 usage

Constant OWNED_ALLOCATION_SUCCESS as Integer is 0
Constant OWNED_ALLOCATION_FAILED as Integer is -1
Constant OWNED_ALLOCATION_OVERFLOW as Integer is -2
Constant OWNED_ALLOCATION_INVALID as Integer is -3

Note:
OWNED_HEAP_STRUCT_SIZE is the on-disk size of the OwnedHeap descriptor in
bytes. The compiler currently lays out the 9-field Type as 9 qwords (72
bytes), but the historical descriptor used a fixed 80-byte allocation because
the initial design reserved a padding qword for future expansion. We retain
the 80-byte allocation to keep the on-disk shape stable across the migration
and to leave room for the future per-allocation chain head pointer.
:End Note

Constant OWNED_HEAP_STRUCT_SIZE as Integer is 80

Note:
PROT_READ_WRITE is the mmap protection mask used by descriptor heaps:
PROT_READ (0x1) | PROT_WRITE (0x2) = 0x3. MAP_PRIVATE_ANON is the mmap flags
mask: MAP_PRIVATE (0x2) | MAP_ANONYMOUS (0x20) = 0x22 (34 decimal). These
match the constants used by runtime/core/memory/arena.runa so that the two
allocators have identical platform behaviour.
:End Note

Constant PROT_READ_WRITE as Integer is 3
Constant MAP_PRIVATE_ANON as Integer is 34

Note:
SYSCALL_MREMAP is the Linux syscall number for mremap. There is no
cross-platform wrapper for mremap in the syscall module (unlike mmap/munmap),
so resize calls the raw syscall_4 dispatch with this number. On non-Linux
platforms owned_heap_resize will fail at runtime; this is documented on the
resize Process @Security_Scope and is the same limitation that the
pre-migration source had.
:End Note

Constant SYSCALL_MREMAP as Integer is 25
Constant MREMAP_MAYMOVE as Integer is 1

Note:
MMAP_ERROR_THRESHOLD is the high-address threshold used to detect mmap and
mremap failure. The syscall ABI on Linux returns a negative errno in the
range -1 .. -4095 on failure, which appears as a very large unsigned address
in the top of the virtual memory space. Any address above (0 - 4096) is
interpreted as an error code. This same threshold convention is used by
arena.runa and matches the kernel mmap ABI documented in <bits/mman-linux.h>.
:End Note

Constant MMAP_ERROR_THRESHOLD as Integer is -4096

Note:
CLOCK_MONOTONIC is the POSIX clock id used by the benchmark Process for
high-resolution timing. SYSCALL_CLOCK_GETTIME is the Linux syscall number;
the chained_arena benchmark uses the same raw syscall pattern with the same
constants, so this is the established convention. The 16-byte timespec layout
(sec at offset 0, nsec at offset 8) is also identical to that file.
:End Note

Constant CLOCK_MONOTONIC as Integer is 1
Constant SYSCALL_CLOCK_GETTIME as Integer is 228
Constant TIMESPEC_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant NANOSECONDS_PER_SECOND as Integer is 1000000000

Note:
============================================================================
OwnedHeap Creation and Destruction
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "owned_heap_create" takes initial_size as Integer, alignment as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Create a fresh descriptor heap with its own mmap-backed data buffer.
        Returns 0 on any sub-allocation failure rather than leaking a half-
        initialized descriptor. The descriptor is small (80 bytes) and lives
        in the global owned heap; the data buffer is mmap'd directly so that
        a large heap does not pollute the owned-heap free list with a huge
        single allocation. mmap also gives the kernel control over physical
        page commit, which keeps the resident set small until the heap is
        actually used.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. Clamp initial_size up to OWNED_HEAP_MIN_SIZE if too small.
               No upper clamp here: an oversized request will fail at the
               mmap syscall, which propagates as 0 below.
            2. Clamp alignment up to 8 if a smaller value was passed. A
               descriptor heap always returns at least 8-byte aligned
               pointers.
            3. Allocate the 80-byte OwnedHeap descriptor from the global
               owned heap. Failure returns 0.
            4. mmap a fresh PROT_READ|PROT_WRITE, MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS
               region of use_size bytes via the cross-platform
               Syscall.syscall_mmap wrapper. fd=-1, offset=0, addr_hint=0.
            5. If mmap returned an error (address greater than the negative
               error threshold), deallocate the descriptor and return 0.
            6. Initialize all 9 fields of the descriptor:
                 memory_block      = mmap_result
                 current_pos       = 0
                 size              = use_size
                 capacity          = use_size
                 alignment         = use_alignment
                 owner             = 0 (caller may set later)
                 is_owned          = 1 (descriptor owns the mmap region)
                 allocation_count  = 0
                 peak_usage        = 0
            7. Return the descriptor pointer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Cost is one owned-heap allocation (descriptor) plus one mmap syscall.
        The mmap is the dominant cost (~1-10 microseconds depending on
        contention and zero-page recycling in the kernel); the descriptor
        allocation is sub-microsecond. Subsequent allocate calls against the
        returned heap are O(1) pointer-bump.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Does not accept any caller-controlled pointer. Validates incoming
        size and alignment. The mmap region is fresh kernel-zeroed memory so
        no stale data is exposed to the caller. The descriptor's owner field
        is set to 0; if a parent subsystem needs ownership tracking it must
        write the owner field after create returns.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Validate initial_size
    Let use_size be initial_size
    If use_size is less than OWNED_HEAP_MIN_SIZE:
        Set use_size to OWNED_HEAP_MIN_SIZE
    End If

    Note: Validate alignment - must be at least 8 bytes
    Let use_alignment be alignment
    If use_alignment is less than 8:
        Set use_alignment to 8
    End If

    Note: Allocate OwnedHeap descriptor (80 bytes)
    Let heap_ptr be proc allocate from MemoryLayout with OWNED_HEAP_STRUCT_SIZE

    If heap_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Allocate mmap-backed data buffer via cross-platform wrapper
    Let addr_hint be 0
    Let fd be 0 minus 1
    Let mmap_offset be 0
    Let memory_block be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with addr_hint, use_size, PROT_READ_WRITE, MAP_PRIVATE_ANON, fd, mmap_offset

    Note: Check for mmap failure - any address above the error threshold is an errno return
    If memory_block is greater than MMAP_ERROR_THRESHOLD:
        Let dummy1 be proc deallocate from MemoryLayout with heap_ptr
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize OwnedHeap descriptor fields
    Let dummy2 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap_ptr, 0, memory_block     Note: memory_block
    Let dummy3 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap_ptr, 8, 0                Note: current_pos = 0
    Let dummy4 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap_ptr, 16, use_size        Note: size
    Let dummy5 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap_ptr, 24, use_size        Note: capacity
    Let dummy6 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap_ptr, 32, use_alignment   Note: alignment
    Let dummy7 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap_ptr, 40, 0               Note: owner = 0
    Let dummy8 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap_ptr, 48, 1               Note: is_owned = true
    Let dummy9 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap_ptr, 56, 0               Note: allocation_count = 0
    Let dummy10 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap_ptr, 64, 0              Note: peak_usage = 0

    Return heap_ptr
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_destroy" takes heap as Integer returns Nothing:
    @Reasoning:
        Tear down a descriptor heap. The mmap region must be returned to the
        kernel via munmap (the owned-heap deallocator cannot release an mmap
        region because it never tracked it), and the descriptor must be
        released to the owned heap so its 80 bytes are reusable. NULL is
        accepted as a no-op for idempotent cleanup paths.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard: return immediately on heap == 0.
            2. Read memory_block (offset 0) and capacity (offset 24).
            3. If memory_block is non-zero, munmap the mmap region using the
               cross-platform Syscall.syscall_munmap wrapper. capacity is the
               size that was mmap'd at create or resize time.
            4. Release the descriptor itself through MemoryLayout.deallocate.

        Note: this Process does not propagate the munmap return value because
        munmap failure on a valid address pair indicates kernel-level state
        corruption that the caller cannot meaningfully recover from.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Cost is one munmap syscall (~1 microsecond) plus one owned-heap free.
        Munmap dominates. After destroy, any pointer previously returned by
        allocate against this heap is invalid and must not be dereferenced.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Caller is responsible for ensuring no live pointers into memory_block
        remain. The function unmaps memory_block from the process address
        space; subsequent reads through stale pointers will fault. Validates
        memory_block != 0 before unmap to avoid passing a null address to
        munmap, which the kernel would reject as EINVAL on most platforms.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Note: Read memory_block and capacity for unmap
    Let memory_block be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 0
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 24

    Note: Unmap the data buffer if it was mapped
    If memory_block is not equal to 0:
        Let dummy1 be proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with memory_block, capacity
    End If

    Note: Free the descriptor itself
    Let dummy2 be proc deallocate from MemoryLayout with heap

    Return
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_reset" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Return the descriptor to a fresh state without releasing the mmap
        region. After reset, the heap behaves as if it were just created:
        allocation_count and peak_usage are both 0, and the bump pointer is
        at 0. This is the canonical "reuse this heap for a new pass" entry
        point - the data buffer stays warm in the cache and the mmap region
        stays committed. Pointers previously returned from this heap are
        invalidated by reset (the underlying bytes are not zeroed, but the
        bump pointer no longer reserves them, so future allocates will reuse
        the same addresses).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard: return 0 on heap == 0.
            2. Set current_pos (offset 8) to 0.
            3. Set allocation_count (offset 56) to 0.
            4. Set peak_usage (offset 64) to 0.
            5. Return 1 to indicate success.

        Note: reset deliberately does NOT zero the underlying data buffer.
        Use owned_heap_clear for that. The non-zeroing behaviour is what
        gives reset its O(1) cost regardless of how much was allocated.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Three qword stores. O(1) regardless of how much memory was allocated
        against the descriptor before reset. This is the fastest reuse path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The underlying data buffer is NOT zeroed. If a security-sensitive
        workload reused this heap and wrote secrets into its allocations, a
        subsequent allocator on the same heap will see those secrets unless
        the caller uses owned_heap_clear (which zeroes) or writes over the
        allocation before reading from it. For cryptographic key material or
        similar high-value data, use owned_heap_clear instead.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Reset bump pointer
    Let dummy1 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8, 0

    Note: Reset allocation count
    Let dummy2 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 56, 0

    Note: Reset peak usage
    Let dummy3 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 64, 0

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_clear" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Zero out the data buffer and reset the bump pointer. Unlike reset,
        clear pays the cost of zeroing the entire size-byte buffer; in
        exchange it guarantees that subsequent allocate calls return memory
        whose initial contents are all zero. Useful when the descriptor was
        previously used for secret data or when the caller wants
        deterministic-zero initial state for the next pass without paying
        per-allocation zero costs.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard: return 0 on heap == 0.
            2. Read memory_block (offset 0) and size (offset 16).
            3. Call memory_zero(memory_block, size) to clear the data buffer.
            4. Reset current_pos (offset 8) to 0. Allocation count and peak
               usage are NOT reset by clear - only by reset/reset_stats. This
               preserves the lifetime-counter semantics: clear is "wipe the
               bytes," reset is "wipe the bookkeeping."
            5. Return 1.

        Migration note (2026-05-18): the pre-migration source documented
        "Does not free heap memory, just resets position" which obscured
        what makes clear different from reset. The behavioural difference -
        clear zeroes the data buffer, reset does not - is now explicit.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        O(size) due to the full-buffer memory_zero. For large heaps this is
        much more expensive than reset. Prefer reset whenever the caller is
        okay with stale data in unreferenced regions of the buffer.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Zeroing the buffer is a defence-in-depth measure that prevents stale
        data from a previous owner leaking into subsequent allocators. Use
        this entry point when the heap previously held sensitive data.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Zero out data buffer
    Let memory_block be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 0
    Let size be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 16

    Let dummy1 be proc memory_zero from MemoryCore with memory_block, size

    Note: Reset bump pointer (allocation_count and peak_usage preserved by design)
    Let dummy2 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8, 0

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_clone" takes source_heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Produce an independent copy of an existing descriptor heap. The
        clone has its own mmap region (created by owned_heap_create) of the
        same size and alignment, and the live byte range (0 .. current_pos)
        of the source buffer is copied byte-for-byte into the clone's
        buffer. After clone returns, mutating either heap has no effect on
        the other. The bookkeeping fields (current_pos, allocation_count,
        peak_usage) are copied from source so that any pointer arithmetic
        based on heap state remains consistent.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard: return 0 on source_heap == 0.
            2. Read source's size (offset 16) and alignment (offset 32).
            3. Create a new heap with the same size and alignment via
               owned_heap_create. Failure propagates as 0.
            4. Read source's memory_block (offset 0), clone's memory_block
               (offset 0), and source's current_pos (offset 8). The
               current_pos value is also the count of bytes that contain
               live data.
            5. memory_copy(dst_block, src_block, current_pos) duplicates the
               live byte range. Bytes beyond current_pos are left as
               kernel-zeroed (the clone's mmap region is fresh).
            6. Set clone's current_pos to source's current_pos.
            7. Set clone's allocation_count from source's allocation_count
               (offset 56).
            8. Set clone's peak_usage from source's peak_usage (offset 64).
            9. Return clone pointer.

        Note: the clone shares no memory with the source. Pointers handed
        out previously by allocate against source point into source's
        memory_block, not the clone's. The clone is a fresh address-space
        with the same logical contents at the same offsets.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Cost is owned_heap_create (one descriptor allocate plus one mmap)
        plus one memory_copy of current_pos bytes. The mmap is the dominant
        cost for small live data; memory_copy dominates for large live data.
        Either way O(current_pos) plus a fixed mmap cost.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The clone observes whatever bytes the source had in its live region.
        If the source was used for secret data, the clone inherits those
        secrets. Caller is responsible for not cloning into a less-trusted
        context. Bytes beyond current_pos are kernel-zeroed in the clone
        regardless of source contents.
    @End Security_Scope

    If source_heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Read source size and alignment
    Let size be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with source_heap, 16
    Let alignment be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with source_heap, 32

    Note: Create new heap with matching dimensions
    Let new_heap be proc owned_heap_create with size, alignment

    If new_heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Copy live byte range
    Let src_block be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with source_heap, 0
    Let dst_block be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with new_heap, 0
    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with source_heap, 8

    Let dummy1 be proc memory_copy from MemoryCore with dst_block, src_block, current_pos

    Note: Mirror bookkeeping fields
    Let dummy2 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with new_heap, 8, current_pos

    Let allocation_count be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with source_heap, 56
    Let dummy3 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with new_heap, 56, allocation_count

    Let peak_usage be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with source_heap, 64
    Let dummy4 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with new_heap, 64, peak_usage

    Return new_heap
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
OwnedHeap Allocation Operations
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "owned_heap_allocate" takes heap as Integer, size as Integer, alignment as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Allocate size bytes from the descriptor heap with the requested
        alignment, using pointer-bump. This is the core allocator entry point;
        all other allocate_* Processes call into this one with derived
        size/alignment arguments. The bump pointer is advanced past the
        allocation; there is no individual free path - the entire heap is
        freed at descriptor destroy/reset/clear time.

        Bump-allocator-under-owned-name (semantic clarification): despite
        the "owned heap" label, this Process implements arena semantics, not
        Tier-3 owned-heap semantics. There is no per-allocation header, no
        free list, no registry tracking, and no individual free. The
        distinction matters because callers who want true Tier-3 owned
        memory (with individual free, registry tracking, generation-based
        use-after-free detection) must use MemoryLayout.allocate directly,
        not this Process. The "owned" qualifier here refers only to the
        owner field on the descriptor (which a parent subsystem may set to
        identify the heap's owner) - it does NOT promise per-allocation
        free.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard: return 0 on heap == 0.
            2. Zero-size guard: return 0 on size == 0 (zero-byte allocations
               are not meaningful for a bump allocator; returning a non-null
               pointer for them would create aliasing risk).
            3. Read current_pos (offset 8) and memory_block (offset 0).
            4. Align current_pos UP to the requested alignment if alignment
               > 1. Uses bitwise_and to find the misalignment then adds the
               complement: aligned_pos = current_pos + ((alignment - (current_pos & (alignment-1))) & (alignment-1))
               implemented in the simpler explicit form: if offset != 0,
               aligned_pos = current_pos + (alignment - offset).
            5. Read capacity (offset 24). Check aligned_pos + size <= capacity.
               If not, return 0 (allocation would overflow the descriptor).
            6. Compute alloc_ptr = memory_block + aligned_pos.
            7. Store the new bump pointer (aligned_pos + size) into
               current_pos.
            8. Increment allocation_count (offset 56) by 1.
            9. If new bump pointer exceeds peak_usage (offset 64), update
               peak_usage so it tracks the lifetime maximum.
           10. Return alloc_ptr.

        Note: this Process does not grow the descriptor on overflow. Callers
        who want auto-growth must build a wrapper that calls
        owned_heap_resize or owned_heap_grow when allocate returns 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        O(1) on the success path: a constant number of memory_get/set ops
        plus a single bitwise_and. No syscalls, no branches into the kernel,
        no cross-cache-line walks. The dominant cost is the memory_get and
        memory_set primitives themselves.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Does not zero the returned memory; the caller observes whatever
        bytes were left in the buffer from a previous allocator. For
        zeroed allocations use owned_heap_allocate_zeroed. The returned
        pointer lies within memory_block .. memory_block + capacity, so
        out-of-bounds writes are impossible up to the allocation size;
        writes BEYOND the returned size may corrupt subsequent allocations
        (the bump allocator does not enforce per-allocation bounds).
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If size is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8
    Let memory_block be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 0

    Note: Align current_pos up to the requested alignment
    Let aligned_pos be current_pos
    If alignment is greater than 1:
        Let mask be alignment minus 1
        Let offset be proc bitwise_and from BitwiseCore with current_pos, mask
        If offset is not equal to 0:
            Let padding be alignment minus offset
            Set aligned_pos to current_pos plus padding
        End If
    End If

    Note: Bounds check
    Let new_pos be aligned_pos plus size
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 24
    If new_pos is greater than capacity:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Compute and record the allocation
    Let alloc_ptr be memory_block plus aligned_pos
    Let dummy1 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8, new_pos

    Note: Update allocation count
    Let allocation_count be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 56
    Let new_count be allocation_count plus 1
    Let dummy2 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 56, new_count

    Note: Update peak usage if exceeded
    Let peak_usage be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 64
    If new_pos is greater than peak_usage:
        Let dummy3 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 64, new_pos
    End If

    Return alloc_ptr
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_allocate_aligned" takes heap as Integer, size as Integer, alignment as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Convenience entry point that forwards directly to owned_heap_allocate.
        Retained as a named Process because callers documenting alignment-
        sensitive allocations (cache-line packing, SIMD-friendly buffers)
        find the explicit name clearer than passing an alignment argument
        through the generic allocate.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Forwards directly: returns owned_heap_allocate(heap, size, alignment).
        No additional logic - alignment is already handled by allocate itself.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Identical to owned_heap_allocate. The wrapper imposes one extra
        call frame, which a sufficiently capable inliner will collapse.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Inherits the security properties of owned_heap_allocate. Returned
        memory is not zeroed.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let result be proc owned_heap_allocate with heap, size, alignment
    Return result
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_allocate_zeroed" takes heap as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Allocate size bytes from the descriptor heap and zero them before
        return. Uses the heap's default 8-byte alignment for the underlying
        allocate. Convenience for callers who want structure-shaped memory
        whose uninitialized field reads return 0 deterministically; pay the
        memset cost in exchange for not having to set every field.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. Forward to owned_heap_allocate with alignment = 8.
            2. If allocate returned 0, propagate the failure.
            3. memory_zero(result, size).
            4. Return result.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        O(size) for the zeroing pass plus the O(1) cost of allocate. For
        small allocations the call overhead dominates; for large
        allocations the memory_zero pass dominates.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The zero pass prevents stale data from a previous allocator in the
        same buffer slot from leaking to the caller. Use this entry point
        when the descriptor heap is reused across security domains.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let default_alignment be 8
    Let result be proc owned_heap_allocate with heap, size, default_alignment

    If result is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let dummy be proc memory_zero from MemoryCore with result, size

    Return result
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_allocate_array" takes heap as Integer, element_size as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Allocate a contiguous array of count elements each of element_size
        bytes. The total size is element_size * count; alignment defaults to
        8 bytes which is sufficient for most primitive element types. For
        wider alignment (16-byte for SIMD, 32-byte for AVX), use
        owned_heap_allocate_aligned with the desired alignment and an
        explicit total size.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. Compute total_size = element_size * count. No overflow check
               here - the underlying allocate will catch overflow via the
               capacity test (a negative or absurdly large total_size will
               not fit in the descriptor).
            2. Forward to owned_heap_allocate with alignment = 8.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Identical to owned_heap_allocate plus one multiplication. The
        returned memory is uninitialized; if zero-initialized array
        elements are required, use owned_heap_allocate_zeroed with the same
        total_size.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Caller is responsible for not exceeding the array bounds when
        writing element data. The descriptor heap does not track per-
        element bounds.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let total_size be element_size multiplied by count
    Let alignment be 8

    Let result be proc owned_heap_allocate with heap, total_size, alignment
    Return result
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_allocate_string" takes heap as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Allocate a C-style null-terminated string buffer with capacity
        length + 1 bytes. The trailing byte is written as 0 so the buffer
        is a valid empty string until the caller fills the prefix. Strings
        are allocated with alignment = 1 because byte addressing of strings
        is the canonical use case and any tighter alignment wastes space.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. buffer_size = length + 1 (room for trailing NUL).
            2. allocate with alignment = 1.
            3. If allocate succeeded, write a 0 byte at offset length so the
               buffer is a valid C string ("\0" at minimum).
            4. Return the buffer pointer.

        Note: this Process does NOT copy any source string into the buffer.
        Callers who want a duplicate of an existing C string must memcpy
        the source after allocate returns.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        owned_heap_allocate cost plus one byte write. The NUL write is the
        cheapest possible side-effect; cost is dominated by the underlying
        allocate.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Returned buffer holds whatever bytes the descriptor's data buffer
        had at the allocation offset (except the trailing NUL). Callers
        reading the buffer as a string before filling it will observe stale
        data up to the first 0 byte (or up to length, whichever is closer).
        Use owned_heap_allocate_zeroed if a fully-zeroed buffer is needed.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let buffer_size be length plus 1
    Let alignment be 1

    Let result be proc owned_heap_allocate with heap, buffer_size, alignment

    If result is not equal to 0:
        Let null_offset be length
        Let dummy be proc memory_set_byte from MemoryCore with result, null_offset, 0
    End If

    Return result
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_allocate_struct" takes heap as Integer, struct_size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Convenience entry point for structure allocations: forwards to
        allocate with alignment = 16 which matches the platform ABI
        requirement for structs containing 16-byte-aligned members
        (long double, __m128, etc.) and over-aligns lighter structs at
        most by 15 bytes of padding per allocation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Forwards: returns owned_heap_allocate(heap, struct_size, 16).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Same as owned_heap_allocate at alignment 16. The 16-byte alignment
        may waste up to 15 bytes per allocation on smaller structs; for
        dense packing of small structs prefer owned_heap_allocate with a
        smaller alignment.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Inherits the security properties of owned_heap_allocate. Returned
        memory is not zeroed.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let alignment be 16

    Let result be proc owned_heap_allocate with heap, struct_size, alignment
    Return result
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
OwnedHeap Memory Management
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "owned_heap_resize" takes heap as Integer, new_size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Resize the descriptor's mmap region to new_size bytes via mremap.
        Allows the kernel to relocate the mapping if needed (MREMAP_MAYMOVE),
        which preserves the existing live byte range at the new address
        without an explicit copy. The descriptor's memory_block, size, and
        capacity are updated to reflect the new mapping. Existing pointers
        handed out by allocate are INVALIDATED if the kernel relocates the
        mapping; callers must not retain pointers across resize unless they
        verified the address did not change.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard.
            2. Read current_pos (offset 8). If new_size < current_pos, the
               live data range would be truncated; return 0 to refuse the
               shrink rather than silently lose data.
            3. Read current memory_block (offset 0) and capacity (offset 24).
            4. Issue raw syscall_4 with SYSCALL_MREMAP, passing
               (memory_block, capacity, new_size, MREMAP_MAYMOVE). No
               cross-platform wrapper exists for mremap so the raw dispatch
               is the only path.
            5. Check the return value against MMAP_ERROR_THRESHOLD - if the
               syscall failed, return 0 and leave the descriptor unchanged.
            6. Update memory_block (offset 0) to the new address.
            7. Update capacity (offset 24) and size (offset 16) to new_size.
               The two fields remain coupled today; future logical/physical
               split would only update capacity here.
            8. Return 1 on success.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Cost is one mremap syscall, which is significantly faster than
        the equivalent munmap + mmap + memcpy sequence because the kernel
        can either extend the mapping in place (~1 microsecond) or move it
        via page-table edits (proportional to the page count of the live
        range, no actual byte copies).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        mremap is Linux-specific. On non-Linux platforms (Darwin, FreeBSD,
        Windows via WSL2 with limitations) this syscall will fail with
        ENOSYS or equivalent, and resize will return 0. The descriptor's
        existing mapping is preserved on failure. Pointers handed out
        before resize are invalidated if the kernel relocated the mapping
        even though resize itself returned successfully - callers must not
        retain pointers across resize.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8
    If new_size is less than current_pos:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let memory_block be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 0
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 24

    Note: mremap is Linux-specific; no cross-platform wrapper exists
    Let new_addr be proc syscall_4 from Syscall with SYSCALL_MREMAP, memory_block, capacity, new_size, MREMAP_MAYMOVE

    If new_addr is greater than MMAP_ERROR_THRESHOLD:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let dummy1 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 0, new_addr
    Let dummy2 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 24, new_size
    Let dummy3 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 16, new_size

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_grow" takes heap as Integer, growth_size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Grow the descriptor's capacity by exactly growth_size bytes (not by
        a multiplicative factor). For doubling-style growth callers should
        pass capacity directly (which doubles current capacity). The simple
        additive form is provided because some callers want bounded growth
        with predictable memory usage.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Reads current capacity (offset 24), computes new_capacity =
        capacity + growth_size, and forwards to owned_heap_resize. The
        resize call performs the actual mremap.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Same as owned_heap_resize. If exponential growth is needed (to
        amortize the resize cost across many small grows), call grow with
        growth_size = current capacity to double.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Inherits Linux-only restriction from owned_heap_resize. Pointers
        previously returned by allocate are invalidated if the kernel
        relocates the mapping during grow.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let capacity be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 24
    Let new_capacity be capacity plus growth_size

    Let result be proc owned_heap_resize with heap, new_capacity
    Return result
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_shrink" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Shrink the descriptor's mmap region down to current_pos plus a
        small headroom buffer. The headroom (1024 bytes) gives the next
        few allocations room to succeed before another grow becomes
        necessary, amortising the cost of repeated shrink/grow cycles in
        steady-state workloads. Used by owned_heap_optimize when the heap
        is below the shrink threshold.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard.
            2. Read current_pos (offset 8).
            3. new_size = current_pos + 1024 (the headroom constant).
            4. Forward to owned_heap_resize. The resize will refuse if
               new_size < current_pos, but here new_size > current_pos by
               construction so the resize is well-defined.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Same as owned_heap_resize. Useful at the end of a workload phase
        to release unused mmap pages back to the kernel; the kernel
        decommits the freed pages on the spot, reducing the process's RSS.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Inherits Linux-only restriction from owned_heap_resize. The
        shrunken region's high-address pages are released to the kernel;
        any data the descriptor held in those pages is lost.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8

    Let headroom be 1024
    Let new_size be current_pos plus headroom

    Let result be proc owned_heap_resize with heap, new_size
    Return result
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_compact" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Bump allocators do not fragment because every allocation is laid
        out contiguously from offset 0 forward. There are no gaps to
        compact away. This Process is therefore a definitional no-op on
        success, retained in the API only for interface uniformity with
        allocators that DO fragment (free-list, slab, buddy). Callers who
        compact-then-validate as a periodic maintenance hook may continue
        to call it on this allocator; the 1 return value indicates that
        the (vacuous) compaction succeeded.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard: return 0 on heap == 0.
            2. Return 1 indicating success (vacuous compaction).

        This is an intentional no-op, not a placeholder. The annotation
        documents why the Process body is short: there is nothing to do.
        Removing this Process would force every caller writing a generic
        allocator-maintenance hook to special-case bump allocators.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        O(1). A single null check and a return; no memory operations.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Does not read or modify the descriptor beyond the null check.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Bump allocators are inherently non-fragmenting - compaction is vacuous.
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_merge" takes heap1 as Integer, heap2 as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Build a fresh descriptor heap whose data buffer holds the
        concatenation of heap1's and heap2's live byte ranges. The
        resulting heap is independent of both sources (they remain valid
        and unchanged). The new heap's capacity is heap1.size + heap2.size,
        its current_pos is heap1.current_pos + heap2.current_pos, its
        allocation_count is the sum of the two sources' counts, and its
        alignment is inherited from heap1. peak_usage is left at 0 in the
        merged heap because the merge operation itself does not have a
        meaningful "peak observed during merge."
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. Reject NULL inputs on either side.
            2. Read size1 (offset 16 of heap1), size2 (offset 16 of heap2),
               and total_size = size1 + size2.
            3. Read alignment from heap1 (offset 32). Inherit only from
               heap1 because alignment requirements are caller-defined and
               we cannot reconcile a conflict; documenting heap1 as the
               authority avoids surprise.
            4. Create the merged heap via owned_heap_create(total_size,
               alignment). Failure propagates as 0.
            5. Read source data block pointers (heap1 offset 0, heap2
               offset 0) and the merged block pointer.
            6. Read live ranges: pos1 = heap1.current_pos, pos2 =
               heap2.current_pos.
            7. memory_copy(merged_block, heap1_block, pos1) copies the
               first heap's live bytes to the start of the merged buffer.
            8. dest_ptr = merged_block + pos1.
               memory_copy(dest_ptr, heap2_block, pos2) appends the second
               heap's live bytes.
            9. Update the merged heap's current_pos to pos1 + pos2.
           10. Read both sources' allocation_count (offset 56), sum them,
               and write the total into the merged heap.
           11. Return the merged heap pointer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Cost is owned_heap_create (one descriptor allocate plus one mmap)
        plus two memory_copies. Linear in total_size. For very large
        merges the two memory_copies dominate; for small merges the
        mmap dominates.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The merged heap contains a verbatim copy of heap1's and heap2's
        live data; if either source held sensitive data, the merged heap
        inherits it. Caller is responsible for not exposing the merged
        heap across a trust boundary that the sources did not cross.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap1 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If heap2 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let size1 be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap1, 16
    Let size2 be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap2, 16
    Let total_size be size1 plus size2

    Let alignment be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap1, 32

    Let merged_heap be proc owned_heap_create with total_size, alignment

    If merged_heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let block1 be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap1, 0
    Let block2 be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap2, 0
    Let merged_block be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with merged_heap, 0

    Let pos1 be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap1, 8
    Let pos2 be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap2, 8

    Let dummy1 be proc memory_copy from MemoryCore with merged_block, block1, pos1

    Let dest_offset be pos1
    Let dest_ptr be merged_block plus dest_offset
    Let dummy2 be proc memory_copy from MemoryCore with dest_ptr, block2, pos2

    Let new_pos be pos1 plus pos2
    Let dummy3 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with merged_heap, 8, new_pos

    Let count1 be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap1, 56
    Let count2 be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap2, 56
    Let total_count be count1 plus count2
    Let dummy4 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with merged_heap, 56, total_count

    Return merged_heap
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
OwnedHeap Query Operations
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "owned_heap_descriptor_get_size" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Return the logical size (in bytes) of the descriptor's data buffer
        - that is, the value of the size field at descriptor offset 16.
        Renamed during migration from owned_heap_get_size to avoid a name
        collision with runtime/core/memory/owned_heap_wrappers.runa's
        owned_heap_get_size (which takes a user-pointer and consults the
        registry, an entirely different signature and semantics). Both
        Processes coexist; this one queries a heap descriptor, the wrapper
        version queries a single allocation's recorded size.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard: return 0 on heap == 0.
            2. Read size from offset 16.
            3. Return the value.

        Pre-migration name: owned_heap_get_size. Zero external callers used
        the old name, so the rename has no caller-side impact.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One qword read. O(1).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Reads only the descriptor metadata, not the data buffer. Safe on
        any descriptor that is not actively being destroyed by another
        thread.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let size be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 16
    Return size
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_get_capacity" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Return the physical capacity (in bytes) of the descriptor's data
        buffer - that is, the value of the capacity field at offset 24. In
        the current design size and capacity always coincide; the fields
        are retained as distinct slots to allow future logical-vs-physical
        distinction.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        NULL guard, then read offset 24 and return it.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One qword read. O(1).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Reads only the descriptor metadata.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let capacity be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 24
    Return capacity
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_get_usage" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Return the current bump pointer position (offset 8) which is also
        the number of bytes currently allocated against the heap. Useful
        for diagnostics, watermark monitoring, and the optimize/shrink
        decision logic in owned_heap_optimize.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        NULL guard, then read offset 8 and return it.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One qword read. O(1).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Reads only the descriptor metadata.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8
    Return current_pos
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_get_peak_usage" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Return the lifetime maximum of current_pos (offset 64). This is the
        canonical "high water mark" metric for capacity planning: how big
        did the heap need to get during this descriptor's lifetime? The
        value persists across reset_stats only if the application sets it
        again after reset; reset_stats deliberately retains the previous
        peak as a baseline (see owned_heap_reset_stats).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        NULL guard, then read offset 64 and return it.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One qword read. O(1).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Reads only the descriptor metadata.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let peak_usage be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 64
    Return peak_usage
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_get_fragmentation" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Bump allocators do not fragment - every allocation is contiguous
        from offset 0 forward. The fragmentation metric is therefore always
        0 by construction. This Process is retained in the API for parity
        with allocators that DO fragment, so a generic
        "compute-allocator-fragmentation" caller can poll all allocators
        uniformly. A non-zero return would be a contract violation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard: return 0 on heap == 0 (matches the "no
               fragmentation" semantics by happy accident; a null heap
               trivially has no gaps).
            2. Return 0 (the genuine no-fragmentation answer for any
               live bump allocator).

        The Return 0 here is the correct computed value, not a placeholder.
        See @Reasoning for the proof.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        O(1). One null check, one return.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Reads no descriptor state.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Bump allocators have no fragmentation by construction.
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_get_allocation_count" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Return the lifetime count of successful allocate calls (offset 56).
        Reset by reset and reset_stats. Useful for diagnostics and average-
        allocation-size calculations in owned_heap_profile.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        NULL guard, then read offset 56 and return it.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One qword read. O(1).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Reads only the descriptor metadata.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let allocation_count be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 56
    Return allocation_count
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_is_full" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Return 1 if the heap has zero free bytes - that is, if current_pos
        >= capacity. A null heap is conservatively reported as full (the
        caller cannot allocate from it) which is more useful than the
        contrary "empty heap" interpretation for the common pattern of
        "allocate if not full".
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard: return 1 (full).
            2. Read current_pos (offset 8) and capacity (offset 24).
            3. If current_pos >= capacity, return 1. Otherwise return 0.

        The >= rather than == is deliberate: if current_pos somehow exceeds
        capacity (which would be a bug in allocate), we still report full
        rather than falsely report space available.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Two qword reads, one comparison. O(1).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Reads only the descriptor metadata.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 24

    If current_pos is greater than or equal to capacity:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_has_space" takes heap as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Return 1 if the heap can accommodate an allocation of size bytes
        WITHOUT considering alignment padding. The omission of alignment is
        deliberate: this is a fast pre-check, not a guarantee, so the
        caller can use it to short-circuit obviously-too-large requests
        without paying for the bitwise-alignment arithmetic. The actual
        allocate call still performs the exact bounds check with alignment.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard: return 0.
            2. Zero-size check: zero bytes always fits, return 1.
            3. Compute space_remaining = capacity - current_pos.
            4. If space_remaining >= size, return 1. Otherwise return 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Two qword reads, one subtraction, one comparison. O(1). Use this
        for fast pre-checks; the underlying allocate will still re-check
        bounds with alignment padding.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Reads only the descriptor metadata. Reports a conservative answer
        if alignment padding would push the allocation past capacity:
        has_space may return 1 in a case where allocate would later
        return 0. Callers must treat has_space as a hint, not a guarantee.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If size is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 24

    Let space_remaining be capacity minus current_pos

    If space_remaining is greater than or equal to size:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
OwnedHeap Performance Operations
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "owned_heap_get_stats" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Allocate and populate a 48-byte OwnedHeapStats blob with current
        statistics from the heap descriptor. The blob is itself an
        allocation from the global owned heap; the caller is responsible
        for releasing it with MemoryLayout.deallocate when done. Returns a
        pointer rather than a stack-copied struct because the v0.0.8.5
        bootstrap compiler does not yet support struct-by-value returns;
        the stats Type is documented in the file header for the day that
        support lands.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard.
            2. Allocate 48 bytes via MemoryLayout.allocate. Failure
               propagates as 0.
            3. Read allocation_count (offset 56) and write to stats offset
               0 (total_allocations).
            4. Read current_pos (offset 8) and write to stats offset 8
               (total_bytes).
            5. Read peak_usage (offset 64) and write to stats offset 16
               (peak_usage).
            6. Write 0 to stats offset 24 (fragmentation - always 0 for
               bump allocator, see owned_heap_get_fragmentation).
            7. Write 0 to stats offsets 32 and 40 (allocation_time and
               deallocation_time - reserved future fields, currently
               always 0).
            8. Return the stats pointer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One owned-heap allocate plus a constant number of memory_get/set
        ops. The allocate is the dominant cost. For polling-style stats
        consumption consider building a caller-side stats buffer and
        re-using it via direct memory_get reads against the descriptor
        rather than calling get_stats repeatedly.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The returned blob is heap-allocated; callers MUST release it via
        MemoryLayout.deallocate to avoid leaking. The blob holds copies of
        descriptor metadata fields and reveals nothing about the heap's
        data buffer contents.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let stats_size be 48
    Let stats_ptr be proc allocate from MemoryLayout with stats_size

    If stats_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let allocation_count be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 56
    Let dummy1 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with stats_ptr, 0, allocation_count

    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8
    Let dummy2 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with stats_ptr, 8, current_pos

    Let peak_usage be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 64
    Let dummy3 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with stats_ptr, 16, peak_usage

    Note: Fragmentation is 0 by construction for bump allocators
    Let dummy4 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with stats_ptr, 24, 0

    Note: allocation_time and deallocation_time reserved for future use
    Let dummy5 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with stats_ptr, 32, 0
    Let dummy6 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with stats_ptr, 40, 0

    Return stats_ptr
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_reset_stats" takes heap as Integer returns Nothing:
    @Reasoning:
        Reset the lifetime allocation counter to 0 and reset peak_usage to
        the current usage. The peak-reset-to-current pattern preserves the
        meaningful invariant peak_usage >= current_pos: after reset_stats
        completes, future allocations will only push peak_usage higher.
        This is different from owned_heap_reset which zeroes both counters
        AND zeroes current_pos; reset_stats is for "I want fresh
        statistics but my heap is mid-workload."
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard: return.
            2. Write 0 to offset 56 (allocation_count).
            3. Read current_pos (offset 8) and write that value to
               offset 64 (peak_usage). Setting peak_usage to current_pos
               (rather than 0) means future calls to get_peak_usage will
               return correct values immediately - if peak_usage were
               zero and current_pos were non-zero, the invariant
               peak_usage >= current_pos would be violated until the
               next allocate.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One read, two writes. O(1).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Modifies only the descriptor metadata. The data buffer is
        unaffected.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let dummy1 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 56, 0

    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8
    Let dummy2 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 64, current_pos

    Return
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_profile" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Build a 40-byte profile blob describing allocation behaviour: how
        utilised is the heap (current_pos / capacity), what is the average
        allocation size, what is the allocation rate, and how much memory
        is wasted (capacity - current_pos). Used for tuning the default
        heap size and triggering owned_heap_optimize. The profile is a
        snapshot - it does not track history between calls.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard.
            2. Allocate 40 bytes from the owned heap for the profile blob.
            3. Read current_pos and capacity. Compute utilization as
               (current_pos * 100) / capacity if capacity > 0, else 0.
               Write to profile offset 0.
            4. Read allocation_count. Compute average_size as current_pos /
               allocation_count if count > 0, else 0. Write to profile
               offset 8.
            5. Write a constant 100 to profile offset 16
               (allocation_efficiency - bump allocators are 100% efficient
               by construction; there is no per-allocation header or
               free-list overhead).
            6. Compute waste = capacity - current_pos and write to
               profile offset 24.
            7. Write allocation_count to profile offset 32
               (allocation_rate proxy - lifetime count is a coarse rate
               estimate when divided by lifetime, which the caller does
               with their own timing).
            8. Return the profile blob pointer.

        Note: the divisions guard against capacity = 0 and
        allocation_count = 0 to avoid a divide-by-zero trap.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One owned-heap allocate plus a constant number of memory_get/set
        ops, two divisions, and one multiplication. Sub-microsecond.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The returned blob is heap-allocated; callers must release it via
        MemoryLayout.deallocate. Reveals only summary metadata - no
        information about the data buffer contents leaks.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let profile_size be 40
    Let profile_ptr be proc allocate from MemoryLayout with profile_size

    If profile_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 24

    Note: Compute utilization percentage, guarded against capacity == 0
    Let utilization be 0
    If capacity is greater than 0:
        Let hundred be 100
        Let numerator be current_pos multiplied by hundred
        Set utilization to numerator divided by capacity
    End If

    Let dummy1 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with profile_ptr, 0, utilization

    Note: Compute average allocation size, guarded against count == 0
    Let allocation_count be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 56
    Let average_size be 0
    If allocation_count is greater than 0:
        Set average_size to current_pos divided by allocation_count
    End If

    Let dummy2 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with profile_ptr, 8, average_size

    Note: Allocation efficiency: 100% for bump allocator (no per-alloc overhead)
    Let efficiency be 100
    Let dummy3 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with profile_ptr, 16, efficiency

    Let waste be capacity minus current_pos
    Let dummy4 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with profile_ptr, 24, waste

    Let dummy5 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with profile_ptr, 32, allocation_count

    Return profile_ptr
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_optimize" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Apply the owned-heap optimization heuristic: if current usage is
        less than a quarter of capacity, shrink the heap down to
        current_pos + headroom. The quarter-capacity threshold balances
        responsiveness (don't shrink prematurely) against memory pressure
        (release unused pages back to the kernel when usage stays low).
        Returns 1 on success (whether or not a shrink was actually
        performed - "the heap is already optimal" is also success).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard.
            2. Read current_pos and capacity.
            3. Compute quarter_capacity = capacity / 4 (integer division;
               the heuristic does not need sub-page precision).
            4. If current_pos < quarter_capacity, call owned_heap_shrink
               and return its result.
            5. Otherwise return 1 (no work needed).

        The threshold is the constant OWNED_HEAP_SHRINK_THRESHOLD = 4,
        documented at the constants block. Changing the threshold here
        would require updating that constant in parallel.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Fast path (no shrink needed): two qword reads, one division, one
        comparison. ~10 nanoseconds. Slow path (shrink): inherits the
        owned_heap_shrink + owned_heap_resize syscall cost.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Inherits Linux-only restriction from owned_heap_resize when the
        shrink path is taken. Pointers handed out by allocate may be
        invalidated if the kernel relocates the mmap region during shrink.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 24

    Let quarter_capacity be capacity divided by 4
    If current_pos is less than quarter_capacity:
        Let result be proc owned_heap_shrink with heap
        Return result
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_benchmark" takes heap as Integer, iterations as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Run an in-place benchmark of the descriptor heap: allocate a
        fixed 64-byte block repeatedly for iterations rounds, measure
        wall-clock time via clock_gettime(CLOCK_MONOTONIC), and report
        allocations-per-second, average per-allocation time in
        nanoseconds, total time, and the iteration count. After the
        benchmark loop the heap is reset so the benchmark does not
        permanently consume capacity.

        The 64-byte fixed allocation size is chosen because it matches a
        typical compiler-data-structure footprint (AST node, IR
        instruction, symbol entry). Callers who want to benchmark
        different allocation profiles can call benchmark with different
        heap configurations.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL/zero-iter guards: return 0 if heap == 0 or iterations
               < 1.
            2. Allocate a 32-byte BenchmarkResults blob from the owned heap.
            3. Allocate a 16-byte timespec scratch buffer from the owned
               heap. clock_gettime writes into this buffer; the buffer is
               freed after the benchmark completes.
            4. Read CLOCK_MONOTONIC start time via syscall_2(228, ...).
               The 228 syscall number is Linux x86_64 clock_gettime;
               chained_arena.runa uses the same constant in its benchmark.
            5. Run the allocate loop: iterations rounds of
               owned_heap_allocate(heap, 64, 8).
            6. Read CLOCK_MONOTONIC end time. Convert both endpoints to
               nanoseconds (sec * 1_000_000_000 + nsec) and subtract.
            7. Write total_time (offset 16), average_time = total / iter
               (offset 8), allocs_per_sec = iter * 1e9 / total
               (offset 0), and iter (offset 24) to the results blob.
            8. Reset the heap to release the iterations*64 bytes that
               were just allocated.
            9. Free the timespec scratch buffer via
               MemoryLayout.deallocate.
           10. Return the results blob pointer (the caller must release
               it with MemoryLayout.deallocate).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Cost is two clock_gettime syscalls plus iterations bump
        allocations plus the heap reset. The benchmark itself is the
        thing being measured. For statistically meaningful results
        choose iterations > 10000 so the syscall overhead is amortised.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Modifies the heap by allocating iterations * 64 bytes and then
        resetting it. Existing pointers handed out by the heap before
        benchmark was called are invalidated by the reset at step 8.
        Callers must ensure no live pointers into the heap exist when
        benchmark is called. The clock_gettime syscall is Linux-specific;
        on other platforms the benchmark will record nonsense times.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If iterations is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let results_size be 32
    Let results_ptr be proc allocate from MemoryLayout with results_size

    If results_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let timespec_ptr be proc allocate from MemoryLayout with TIMESPEC_SIZE

    Note: Get start timestamp via clock_gettime(CLOCK_MONOTONIC)
    Let dummy1 be proc syscall_2 from Syscall with SYSCALL_CLOCK_GETTIME, CLOCK_MONOTONIC, timespec_ptr

    Let start_sec be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with timespec_ptr, 0
    Let start_nsec be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with timespec_ptr, 8
    Let start_time be start_sec multiplied by NANOSECONDS_PER_SECOND
    Set start_time to start_time plus start_nsec

    Note: Run the benchmark loop
    Let test_size be 64
    Let alignment be 8
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than iterations:
        Let alloc_ptr be proc owned_heap_allocate with heap, test_size, alignment
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Get end timestamp
    Let dummy2 be proc syscall_2 from Syscall with SYSCALL_CLOCK_GETTIME, CLOCK_MONOTONIC, timespec_ptr

    Let end_sec be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with timespec_ptr, 0
    Let end_nsec be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with timespec_ptr, 8
    Let end_time be end_sec multiplied by NANOSECONDS_PER_SECOND
    Set end_time to end_time plus end_nsec

    Let total_time be end_time minus start_time
    Let dummy3 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with results_ptr, 16, total_time

    Let average_time be 0
    If iterations is greater than 0:
        Set average_time to total_time divided by iterations
    End If
    Let dummy4 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with results_ptr, 8, average_time

    Let allocs_per_sec be 0
    If total_time is greater than 0:
        Let iterations_times_billion be iterations multiplied by NANOSECONDS_PER_SECOND
        Set allocs_per_sec to iterations_times_billion divided by total_time
    End If
    Let dummy5 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with results_ptr, 0, allocs_per_sec

    Let dummy6 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with results_ptr, 24, iterations

    Note: Reset the heap to release the benchmark's allocations
    Let dummy7 be proc owned_heap_reset with heap

    Note: Free the timespec scratch buffer
    Let dummy8 be proc deallocate from MemoryLayout with timespec_ptr

    Return results_ptr
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
OwnedHeap Debugging Operations
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "owned_heap_validate" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Sanity-check the descriptor's metadata fields against a set of
        invariants that any live descriptor MUST satisfy:
            - heap != null
            - memory_block != null (the data buffer must exist)
            - current_pos in [0, capacity]
            - size <= capacity
            - allocation_count >= 0
            - peak_usage <= capacity

        Any violation indicates either a corrupted descriptor or a use-
        after-destroy. Returns 0 on any violation so that callers can
        early-out before touching the underlying data buffer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Sequential checks of each invariant, returning 0 at the first
        violation. The checks are ordered cheapest-to-most-expensive
        (null check first, then field reads, then arithmetic comparisons)
        so that the common "all good" path is fast and the common
        failure modes are caught early.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Best case: one null check (~1ns). Worst case (all checks): six
        memory reads and six comparisons (~50ns). O(1) regardless.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Reads only the descriptor metadata; does not dereference
        memory_block. Safe to call on a descriptor whose data buffer has
        already been unmapped but whose 80-byte header is still
        accessible.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let memory_block be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 0
    If memory_block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 24

    If current_pos is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If current_pos is greater than capacity:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let size be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 16
    If size is greater than capacity:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let allocation_count be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 56
    If allocation_count is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let peak_usage be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 64
    If peak_usage is greater than capacity:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_dump" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Snapshot the descriptor state into a 64-byte debug blob suitable
        for logging, post-mortem analysis, or comparison across
        diagnostic checkpoints. Captures: memory_block pointer, current
        bump pointer, size, capacity, allocation count, peak usage, the
        valid/corrupted flag (computed via owned_heap_validate), and a
        utilisation percentage. The returned blob is allocated from the
        owned heap; caller must release it.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard.
            2. Allocate 64 bytes for the dump blob.
            3. For each of memory_block, current_pos, size, capacity,
               allocation_count, peak_usage: read from descriptor at
               documented offset, write to dump blob at the corresponding
               offset (0, 8, 16, 24, 32, 40 respectively).
            4. Call owned_heap_validate(heap) and write the 0/1 result to
               offset 48 (is_valid field).
            5. Compute utilization = (current_pos * 100) / capacity if
               capacity > 0 else 0. Write to offset 56.
            6. Return the dump pointer.

        Dump field layout (documented in the file header above as well):
            offset  0: memory_block_ptr
            offset  8: current_position
            offset 16: size
            offset 24: capacity
            offset 32: allocation_count
            offset 40: peak_usage
            offset 48: is_valid
            offset 56: utilization_percent
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One owned-heap allocate plus six memory reads, eight memory
        writes, one division, one multiplication. Sub-microsecond.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Returned blob is heap-allocated; caller must release. The blob
        reveals the data buffer's address (memory_block) which is sensitive
        on platforms with ASLR; callers should not log dump blobs without
        a security review on hardened deployments.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let dump_size be 64
    Let dump_ptr be proc allocate from MemoryLayout with dump_size

    If dump_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let memory_block be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 0
    Let dummy1 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with dump_ptr, 0, memory_block

    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8
    Let dummy2 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with dump_ptr, 8, current_pos

    Let size be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 16
    Let dummy3 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with dump_ptr, 16, size

    Let capacity be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 24
    Let dummy4 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with dump_ptr, 24, capacity

    Let allocation_count be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 56
    Let dummy5 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with dump_ptr, 32, allocation_count

    Let peak_usage be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 64
    Let dummy6 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with dump_ptr, 40, peak_usage

    Let is_valid be proc owned_heap_validate with heap
    Let dummy7 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with dump_ptr, 48, is_valid

    Let utilization be 0
    If capacity is greater than 0:
        Let hundred be 100
        Let numerator be current_pos multiplied by hundred
        Set utilization to numerator divided by capacity
    End If
    Let dummy8 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with dump_ptr, 56, utilization

    Return dump_ptr
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_trace" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Snapshot allocation history into a 48-byte trace blob. Distinct
        from owned_heap_dump in that dump captures POSITION state
        (current_pos, capacity, is_valid) while trace captures HISTORY
        state (total allocations, average size). Per-allocation history
        is not tracked today; the trace reports aggregate metrics derived
        from the descriptor's lifetime counters. Future per-allocation
        tracking (via the OwnedAllocation Type's reserved fields) would
        produce a richer trace; the current shape is forward-compatible.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard.
            2. Allocate 48 bytes for the trace blob.
            3. Read allocation_count and current_pos.
            4. Write total_allocations (offset 0) = allocation_count.
            5. Write total_bytes_allocated (offset 8) = current_pos. This
               is the lifetime byte total because bump allocators never
               free individually - current_pos is the cumulative total.
            6. Write current_allocations (offset 16) = allocation_count
               (every allocation is "current" - bump allocators do not
               distinguish current from freed).
            7. Compute average_size = current_pos / allocation_count when
               count > 0, else 0.
            8. Write largest_allocation (offset 24), smallest_allocation
               (offset 32), and average_allocation_size (offset 40) all
               to average_size. The largest/smallest fields would require
               per-allocation tracking to populate distinctly; today they
               report the average, with the understanding that this is
               the best aggregate available from descriptor-level
               counters.
            9. Return the trace blob.

        Note on trace fidelity: the largest/smallest fields are not
        false-precision; they are documented as average aggregates in the
        absence of per-allocation tracking. A future enhancement that
        populates the OwnedAllocation chain would update this Process to
        scan the chain for true min/max.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One owned-heap allocate plus a handful of memory ops and one
        division. Sub-microsecond.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Returned blob is heap-allocated; caller must release. Reveals
        only summary lifetime metrics; no information about individual
        allocations or their contents leaks.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let trace_size be 48
    Let trace_ptr be proc allocate from MemoryLayout with trace_size

    If trace_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let allocation_count be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 56
    Let dummy1 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with trace_ptr, 0, allocation_count

    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8
    Let dummy2 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with trace_ptr, 8, current_pos

    Let dummy3 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with trace_ptr, 16, allocation_count

    Let average_size be 0
    If allocation_count is greater than 0:
        Set average_size to current_pos divided by allocation_count
    End If

    Let dummy4 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with trace_ptr, 24, average_size
    Let dummy5 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with trace_ptr, 32, average_size
    Let dummy6 be proc memory_set_integer from MemoryCore with trace_ptr, 40, average_size

    Return trace_ptr
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_check_leaks" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Report the number of "leaked" allocations: allocations that are
        still live (current_pos > 0) when the caller expected the heap
        to be drained. Returns allocation_count when both
        allocation_count > 0 and current_pos > 0 simultaneously - that
        is, "the heap holds N allocations that nobody freed before
        leak-check ran." Returns 0 when the heap is empty (no leaks by
        definition) or when allocation_count is 0 (heap was never used).

        Note that this is descriptor-scoped leak detection, not process-
        scoped. A bump allocator does not have individual frees, so
        "leak" here means "the descriptor was not reset/destroyed before
        leak check fired."
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard.
            2. Read allocation_count (offset 56) and current_pos
               (offset 8).
            3. If allocation_count > 0 AND current_pos > 0, return
               allocation_count.
            4. Otherwise return 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Two qword reads and two comparisons. O(1).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Reads only descriptor metadata. Reports a coarse "did the user
        forget to drain this heap?" signal. Cannot identify individual
        leaked allocations because they are not tracked individually.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let allocation_count be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 56
    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8

    If allocation_count is greater than 0:
        If current_pos is greater than 0:
            Return allocation_count
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "owned_heap_verify" takes heap as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Deeper than validate: in addition to validate's invariants,
        verify checks consistency between related fields (current_pos
        <= size, peak_usage >= current_pos) and confirms the
        memory_block pointer is 8-byte aligned (a freshly-mmap'd page
        is page-aligned, so any non-8-aligned memory_block indicates
        descriptor corruption). Use verify when you suspect descriptor
        damage and want a more thorough check than validate provides.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard.
            2. Call owned_heap_validate. If validate failed, return 0.
            3. Read memory_block, current_pos, size, capacity from the
               descriptor.
            4. Verify current_pos <= size (the bump pointer cannot
               exceed the logical size of the buffer).
            5. Verify size <= capacity.
            6. Read allocation_count; verify it's not negative.
            7. Read peak_usage; verify peak_usage >= current_pos and
               peak_usage <= capacity.
            8. Check that memory_block & 7 == 0 (8-byte alignment).
            9. Return 1 if all checks pass.

        Note on the validate + verify redundancy: validate already
        checks current_pos <= capacity and peak_usage <= capacity, so
        those are repeated here for explicitness. The additional checks
        unique to verify are: current_pos <= size (intra-descriptor
        consistency), peak_usage >= current_pos (peak invariant), and
        memory_block & 7 == 0 (page alignment).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        validate cost plus a handful of additional reads and comparisons.
        ~100 nanoseconds total. Use only at debug checkpoints, not in
        hot paths.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Reads only descriptor metadata. Does not dereference
        memory_block. Safe to call on a descriptor whose data buffer
        has been unmapped.
    @End Security_Scope

    If heap is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let is_valid be proc owned_heap_validate with heap
    If is_valid is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let memory_block be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 0
    Let current_pos be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 8
    Let size be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 16
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 24

    Note: Intra-descriptor consistency: bump pointer within logical size
    If current_pos is greater than size:
        Return 0
    End If

    If size is greater than capacity:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let allocation_count be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 56
    If allocation_count is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let peak_usage be proc memory_get_integer from MemoryCore with heap, 64
    If peak_usage is less than current_pos:
        Return 0
    End If

    If peak_usage is greater than capacity:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: memory_block must be at least 8-byte aligned (mmap returns page-aligned)
    Let alignment_mask be 7
    Let offset be proc bitwise_and from BitwiseCore with memory_block, alignment_mask
    If offset is not equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process
